===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}

# {{lb|en|archaic|formal|or|literary}} From [[where]]; from which [[place]] or [[source]].
#: {{ux|en|'''Whence''' came I?}}
#: {{ux|en|"Pork" comes from French, '''whence''' we get most of our modern cooking terms.}}
#* {{RQ:King James Version|John|8|14|page=1329|column=1|passage=Ieſus anſwered, and ſaid vnto them, Though I beare record of my ſelfe, yet my record is true: for I know '''whence''' I came, and [[whither]] I goe: but ye cannot tell '''whence''' I come, and [[whither]] I goe.}}
#* {{RQ:Mary Shelley Frankenstein|volume=I|chapter=III|pages=81–82|pageref=81|passage='''Whence''', I often asked myself, did the principle of life proceed?}}
#* {{RQ:Stevenson Treasure Island|The Sea Chest|29|[W]hat greatly encouraged me, it was in an opposite direction from that '''whence''' the blind man had made his appearance, and [[whither]] he had presumably returned.}}
#* {{RQ:R. F. Burton Arabian Nights|VI|The Seventh Voyage of Sindbad the Seaman|71|{{...}}But when I had bestridden the plank, quoth I to myself, "Thou deservest all that betideth thee. All this is decreed to me of Allah (whose name be exalted!), to turn me from my greed of gain, '''whence''' ariseth all that I endure, for I have wealth galore."}}
#* {{RQ:Falkner Moonfleet|chapter=A Discovery|page=47|passage=At first I could not tell what this new sound was, nor '''whence''' it came, and now it seemed a little noise close by, and now a great noise in the distance. And then it grew nearer and more defined, and in a moment I knew it was the sound of voices talking.}}

====Usage notes====
* This word is uncommon in contemporary usage; ''from where'' is now usually substituted (as in the example sentence: ''Where did I come from?'' or ''From where did I come?''). ''Whence'' is now mainly encountered in older works and in poetic or literary writing.
* ''From whence'' has a strong literary precedent, appearing in Wyclif's Bible translation, Shakespeare and the King James Bible, as well as in the writings of numerous Victorian-era writers. In recent times, however, it has been criticized as redundant by usage commentators.

